 for bestpractices and # About / Help

## Overview
Create a public-facing About / Help center for Roam Resort that presents brand information, guides guests through the inquiry process, and provides self-service support via FAQs, contact options, and policy links. This page should convey premium editorial aesthetics, be accessible, responsive, and require minimal friction for users to learn about Roam Resort and initiate inquiries. The component should be self-contained but ready to integrate with the existing guest experience (inquiry flow) and admin workflows.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A public About / Help page for Roam Resort that combines brand storytelling with practical support resources. It includes a Brand Story section, an FAQ accordion addressing common inquiry-related questions, a Contact section with a form or direct contact options, and guidance on the inquiry process (from initial interest to concierge follow-up and payment). It also provides legal links (Privacy, Terms, Cookie policy).

Goals:
- Build trust and clarity around the Roam Resort brand and the inquiry process.
- Provide quick access to support channels and self-serve resources.
- Lead guests into the inquiry flow with clear guidance and accessible CTAs.
- Ensure accessibility, responsive behavior, and alignment with the brand’s luxury editorial aesthetic.

Connected features:
- FAQ accordion (internal state, expand/collapse).
- Contact form that routes to the concierge team (email or ticketing endpoint).
- CTA linking to the inquiry flow (guest authentication as needed).
- Legal policy links (privacy, terms, cookie policy) routed to appropriate pages or modal disclosures.

UI elements and visual guidance:
- Brand Story Section: A concise mission overview with editorial typography and an immersive hero feel (background image or accent visuals, centered composition, generous spacing).
- FAQ Accordion: A list of frequently asked questions with expandable/collapsible items. Each item shows a question (header) and answer (panel) with smooth transitions.
- Contact Form: Lightweight support form collecting name, email, inquiry subject, and message or selecting predefined contact topics; validation and success confirmation. Submits to concierge email or an API endpoint.
- Links: Privacy, Terms, Cookie policy in the footer or a secondary navigation panel.
- Visual tone: Luxury editorial, large imagery, refined typography, ample whitespace, soft shadows, and bronze-gold accent CTAs.

API integrations:
- No external APIs required for this task; ensure the contact form is wired to an internal API route (e.g., /api/support/contact) or a serverless function to email/queue the concierge team. If no backend is available in this prompt, implement a mock endpoint structure and validation.

## Components to Build
- AboutHeroSection
  - Purpose: Brand storytelling hero with mission statement and CTA to “Request a Stay” or “Learn How to Inquire”.
  - Props: title, subtitle, backgroundImage, ctaLabel, ctaHref.
  - Behavior: Centered content, responsive typography, accessible alt text, keyboard navigable CTA.

- BrandStoryBlock
  - Purpose: Expanded brand narrative with editorial copy and supporting visuals.
  - Props: paragraphs, image, imageCaption.
  - Behavior: Content blocks with left/right alignment variants for responsive layouts.

- FAQAccordion
  - Purpose: Expandable FAQ list about inquiries, payments, host policies.
  - Props: faqs[] where each item has id, question, answer.
  - Behavior: Accordion with single-open or multiple-open options. Keyboard accessible (Enter/Space to toggle). Uses (items ?? []) mapping with guards.
  - Runtime safety: Ensure (faqs ?? []) is guarded; do not call map on null.

- ContactForm
  - Purpose: Collect contact details and message for concierge.
  - Props: onSubmit callback (optional for testing).
  - Fields: name, email, topic (dropdown), message.
  - Validation: Required fields; email format; length limits.
  - Behavior: On submit, validate, show success message, optionally call an API endpoint (e.g., /api/support/contact) with payload, and reset form on success.
  - Runtime safety: Initialize with proper useState([]) for any list fields; use Array.isArray guards where mapping.

- LegalLinksRow
  - Purpose: Footer or secondary navigation links (Privacy, Terms, Cookie policy).
  - Props: links[] with label and href.
  - Behavior: Accessible links with proper focus styles; responsive wrap.

- PageLayoutShell
  - Purpose: Global About / Help page container providing consistent typography, spacing, and responsive behavior per design system.
  - Props: children; optional pageMeta (title, description).

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React with TypeScript (assuming a modern React stack used by the project).
- State management: useState and useEffect as needed; avoid uncontrolled components without defaults.
- Accessibility: ARIA roles, semantic HTML, keyboard navigable accordions, proper labels.
- Styling: Implement using the project’s design system tokens consistent with the Visual Style section below. Use CSS-in-JS or CSS modules as per project conventions.
- Data safety:
  - Always guard arrays to prevent null/undefined issues: e.g., (faqs ?? []).map(...); Array.isArray(faqs) ? faqs.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize arrays in useState: const [faqs, setFaqs] = useState<FAQItem[]>([]);
- Form handling:
  - ContactForm: local validation; on successful submission, show a toast or inline success state. Do not assume API responses; validate before calling API.
- Routing:
  - Ensure the page is accessible at /about-help or /about. The CTA buttons should navigate to the inquiry flow or login if authentication is required.
- Data loading safeguards:
  - If any data is fetched (e.g., FAQs from CMS), guard with data ?? [] and ensure lists are always arrays before mapping.

### Backend
- API Endpoints (for architecture and integration purposes):
  - POST /api/support/contact
    - Request body: { name: string, email: string, topic?: string, message: string }
    - Response: { ok: boolean, message?: string, ticketId?: string }
  - Optional: GET /api/pages/about-help/faqs (for CMS-driven FAQs)
- Database/REST layer:
  - If a CMS is used, store FAQs as a simple array in the response; sanitize inputs. Use null-safe mapping: Array.isArray(response?.faqs) ? response.faqs : [].
- Security:
  - Validate inputs on server; sanitize to prevent injection. Require authentication for actions beyond public inquiry? For the Help page, public access is allowed; the contact form should not require login.
- Validation:
  - Server should validate required fields, email format, and message length.

### Integration
- Page components should consume data safely (e.g., faqs) with guards:
  - const faqItems = Array.isArray(faqs) ? faqs : [];
- When wiring the ContactForm, use a unified API layer that handles errors and returns a standardized payload. Use appropriate headers and avoid leaking internal errors to the client.
- Ensure consistent design tokens across components (colors, typography, spacing) as defined in Visual Style.

## User Experience Flow
1. User lands on About / Help page, hero presents Roam Resort brand positioning, with a primary CTA to “Request a Stay” and secondary path to “Learn How to Inquire.”
2. Brand Story section presents Roam Resort’s mission in editorial style with supporting visuals.
3. User scrolls to FAQAccordion to find answers about inquiries, payments, host policies; can expand/collapse FAQs with smooth transitions.
4. User can use the ContactForm to reach concierge with questions or feedback; upon submission, input is validated, a success state is shown, and the payload is sent to the backend.
5. Footer includes legal policy links (Privacy, Terms, Cookie policy).
6. If user wants to begin an inquiry, they click the CTA to the Inquiry flow; they may be prompted to login if required by the guest flow.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models:
- FAQItem
  - id: string
  - question: string
  - answer: string
- ContactPayload
  - name: string
  - email: string
  - topic?: string
  - message: string

API Endpoints:
- GET /api/pages/about-help/faqs
  - Response: { data?: FAQItem[] }
- POST /api/support/contact
  - Request: { name: string; email: string; topic?: string; message: string }
  - Response: { ok: boolean; ticketId?: string; message?: string }

Security:
- Public page; no authentication required.
- Contact endpoint should protect against spam (basic rate limiting or CAPTCHA placeholder if implemented). Validate inputs server-side.
- Ensure no sensitive data exposure in responses.

Validation:
- Client:
  - Name: required, max length 100
  - Email: required, valid email
  - Topic: optional, one of predefined topics
  - Message: required, min length 10, max 2000
- Server:
  - Same validations; sanitize strings; reject invalid inputs with 400 and helpful messages.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The About / Help page renders with Brand Story, FAQAccordion, ContactForm, and legal links.
- [ ] FAQAccordion supports at least 5 items with proper expand/collapse functionality and keyboard accessibility.
- [ ] ContactForm validates inputs on the client; on submit, calls /api/support/contact and handles success and error states gracefully.
- [ ] All array usage guards against null/undefined data (e.g., data ?? [] or Array.isArray guards).
- [ ] Use useState<T[]>([]) for any array state; ensure no direct calls to array methods on potentially null values.
- [ ] UI adheres to the provided design system and color palette, with responsive behavior and accessible contrast.

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Honor the luxury editorial, premium feel, warmth, and clarity.
- Maintain generous spacing: 40–80px vertical rhythm between sections; 24–32px internal padding in blocks.
- Typography: Playfair Display (or equivalent) for headlines; Inter/Lato for body.
- Centered hero layout; left-aligned content sections; ensure hierarchy and readability.
- Interactive elements: bronze-gold (#A97C50) CTAs; soft beige backgrounds; hover/active states with subtle glow or scale.
- Cards: 8–12px radius, light borders, inner shadows for elevation.
- Navigation: top navbar with transparent overlays on hero; solid-on-scroll; accessible focus states.

Visual Style
Follow the exact color, typography, and component styling guidelines provided:
- Primary: #23212A
- Secondary: #ECE1D4
- Accent: #A97C50
- Text: #F8F6F3 (headings) and #3A3732 (body)
- Details: Gradients with #B49587 to #23212A, #D1B7A1
- Typography: Playfair Display (headlines) + Inter/Lato (body)
- Spacing and layout: as described above

Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety
CRITICAL: All generated code must guard against null/undefined before calling array methods.
1) Supabase-like results: use data ?? [] (if applicable). For this prompt, ensure guards in data handling.
2) Array methods: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
3) useState for arrays: useState<Type[]>([]) initialization.
4) API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
5) Optional chaining: use obj?.property?.nested when accessing API data.
6) Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {};

Project Context Integration Notes
- TARGET PAGE: About / Help
- No connected features listed beyond the page components.
- Ensure the page is self-contained, visually aligned with Roam Resort’s premium editorial aesthetic, and prepared for later integration with the broader guest/inquiry workflows.

Example file structure (suggested):
- src/pages/AboutHelp.tsx
- src/components/AboutHeroSection.tsx
- src/components/BrandStoryBlock.tsx
- src/components/FAQAccordion.tsx
- src/components/ContactForm.tsx
- src/components/LegalLinksRow.tsx
- src/api/support.ts (mock or real API wrapper)
- src/styles/aboutHelp.css or styled-components theme tokens

Notes for AI development tool
- Ensure all components export clean React components with explicit prop types.
- Implement robust unit tests or storybook stories for each component, focusing on null-safety and accessibility.
- Include error boundaries where appropriate.
- Ensure SSR compatibility if the project uses SSR (avoid browser-only globals in rendering paths).

